WEBVTT

00:08.975 --> 00:11.277
Sometimes in our collective
consciousness...

00:11.311 --> 00:12.846
Whoa, there's a whale!

00:12.879 --> 00:14.848
...a place can be reduced
to a cliche...

00:14.881 --> 00:17.517
I didn't expect Hawaii
to look like this at all.

00:17.550 --> 00:20.620
Reedus:
...but often, the reality's
nothing as it seems.

00:20.653 --> 00:23.423
♪♪

00:23.456 --> 00:26.860
This is a land of
sweeping contrast

00:26.893 --> 00:29.629
and impeccable beauty,

00:29.662 --> 00:33.199
perpetually being destroyed
and created,

00:33.233 --> 00:37.604
but in many ways
untouched by time.

00:37.637 --> 00:39.806
This is the Big Island
of Hawaii,

00:39.839 --> 00:42.809
one of the most remote,
inhabited places in the world.

00:42.842 --> 00:45.045
That is just stupid-pretty.

00:45.078 --> 00:55.055
♪♪

00:55.088 --> 00:59.859
♪♪

01:01.528 --> 01:04.431
[Airplane passing]

01:08.568 --> 01:10.904
Arriving on the Big Island...

01:10.937 --> 01:12.338
[Sheep baaing]

01:12.372 --> 01:14.441
this wasn't exactly
what I had in mind.

01:15.675 --> 01:17.243
[Sheep baas]

01:17.277 --> 01:19.412
What I envisioned was
a little more like this.

01:19.446 --> 01:22.816
[Hawaiian music plays]

01:22.849 --> 01:24.551
But let's be honest,

01:24.584 --> 01:28.855
that kind of schtick
was never really my scene,

01:28.888 --> 01:31.825
which is what brought me
to the Big Island.

01:31.858 --> 01:35.495
♪♪

01:35.528 --> 01:38.498
It's so pretty out here.

01:38.531 --> 01:40.700
These mountains in the
background are so beautiful.

01:40.733 --> 01:43.503
You know what I mean.
And the weather is perfect.

01:43.536 --> 01:45.738
It's so beautiful here.
All right, let's hit it.

01:45.772 --> 01:47.373
[Motorcycle engine starts]

01:47.407 --> 01:49.275
♪♪

01:49.309 --> 01:52.512
I made my first visit
to these islands in 2010

01:52.545 --> 01:54.781
to shoot the pilot
for "Hawaii Five-0."

01:54.814 --> 01:57.550
I flew into Honolulu
and got killed off

01:57.584 --> 02:01.354
and spent a few days playing
tourist on the beaches of Oahu.

02:01.387 --> 02:03.289
But this time I'm trading
those tourist traps

02:03.323 --> 02:04.891
for a road less traveled.

02:04.924 --> 02:07.193
♪♪

02:07.227 --> 02:10.063
When people think of Hawaii,
they picture Waikiki

02:10.096 --> 02:12.132
and little do they know
the Big Island

02:12.165 --> 02:14.033
is actually very unique.

02:14.067 --> 02:17.070
For me, I think the Big Island
is just so magical.

02:17.103 --> 02:19.539
Big Island specifically,
is probably one of

02:19.572 --> 02:21.441
the most amazing islands
you'll ever find.

02:21.474 --> 02:22.976
One day, you can go up
to the mountain

02:23.009 --> 02:24.611
and play in the snow
and by the end of the day,

02:24.644 --> 02:26.312
you can be down at the beach,

02:26.346 --> 02:28.748
eating your poke with some poi
and some beers.

02:28.781 --> 02:30.416
[Laughs]

02:30.450 --> 02:32.886
I don't ever want to live
anyplace else.

02:32.919 --> 02:34.621
Reedus: Before heading out,
I'm meeting up

02:34.654 --> 02:37.390
with my good friend,
photographer Patrick Hoelck

02:37.423 --> 02:39.492
to load up on some local moco,

02:39.526 --> 02:42.896
the go-to comfort food
for the locals.

02:42.929 --> 02:44.931
[Bell rings]

02:44.964 --> 02:46.599
Is that us?
<b></b>
Hoelck: Yes.

02:46.633 --> 02:48.067
I'll get it.
You got it?

02:48.101 --> 02:49.435
♪♪

02:49.469 --> 02:51.271
[Laughs]

02:51.304 --> 02:53.006
Is this the local,
local thingie thing we want?

02:53.039 --> 02:55.341
Woman: Yes, it is.
<b></b>
Loco moco.

02:55.375 --> 02:56.776
Patrick and I first met back

02:56.809 --> 02:58.945
in the '90s...
<b></b>
Wow, look at this.

02:58.978 --> 03:01.147
...crossing paths
in New York and L.A.

03:01.181 --> 03:03.583
Wow.
<b></b>
He'd spent some time
surfing in Oahu,

03:03.616 --> 03:07.587
but like me, he's never seen
the Big Island up close.

03:07.620 --> 03:10.256
And sometimes the best way
to unmask an old friend

03:10.290 --> 03:12.425
is by taking a new journey.

03:12.458 --> 03:14.761
I think I want to try soy sauce,
if that's what you do.

03:14.794 --> 03:17.163
It's just an egg,
a burger, rice, and gravy.

03:17.197 --> 03:18.932
Yeah.
<b></b>
Mm.

03:18.965 --> 03:20.700
Not bad.
<b></b>
It's good.

03:20.733 --> 03:23.436
A renowned filmmaker
and director,

03:23.469 --> 03:24.837
Patrick's also
one of Hollywood's

03:24.871 --> 03:27.540
most sought-after photographers.

03:27.574 --> 03:29.642
And you're so easy-going
and it just felt like

03:29.676 --> 03:31.110
we were hanging out
like we always do.

03:31.144 --> 03:33.313
You must get stories
while you do that,

03:33.346 --> 03:34.948
that you wouldn't
normally get?

03:34.981 --> 03:37.951
Yeah, like when you talked
about your dishwashing

03:37.984 --> 03:39.852
with the Clash songs
with your mother.

03:39.886 --> 03:41.154
We didn't have
a washing machine,

03:41.187 --> 03:42.555
right, so we'd just do
the dishes together,

03:42.589 --> 03:44.791
but she -- she, you know,
had the old turntable

03:44.824 --> 03:46.960
and the big speakers
and she would blast,

03:46.993 --> 03:50.496
you know, that song and sing it
and she taught me the words.

03:50.530 --> 03:54.400
I've known you forever
and I've never heard that.

03:54.434 --> 03:56.402
Yeah.
<b></b>
It took this thing
to just --

03:56.436 --> 03:57.804
it just came up.

03:57.837 --> 03:58.805
Are you ready
to get out of here?

03:58.838 --> 04:01.174
Done.
<b></b>
All right, let's roll.

04:01.207 --> 04:02.575
[Motorcycle engine revs]

04:02.609 --> 04:04.043
Let's go explore.

04:04.077 --> 04:07.981
♪♪

04:08.014 --> 04:10.416
Perfect weather.
Whoo!

04:10.450 --> 04:11.985
♪ Filling negative space ♪

04:12.018 --> 04:13.820
Patrick,
we're in Hawaii, man.

04:13.853 --> 04:16.155
Yeah!
<b></b>
♪ You left here
without a chase ♪

04:16.189 --> 04:18.825
♪ Coming after redemption,
you came ♪

04:18.858 --> 04:21.427
♪ Left me without my faith ♪

04:21.461 --> 04:23.997
♪ Heart beatin' ♪

04:24.030 --> 04:26.399
♪ Heart beating low ♪

04:26.432 --> 04:29.002
♪ Your heart beats so slow ♪

04:29.035 --> 04:31.204
Over the next three days,
we'll zigzag through

04:31.237 --> 04:33.573
this 4,000-square-mile island,

04:33.606 --> 04:36.442
using its main coastal beltway
as our guide.

04:36.476 --> 04:38.611
We'll pass through
tropical rainforests,

04:38.645 --> 04:41.948
sun-soaked beaches,
and snow-capped mountains,

04:41.981 --> 04:43.850
making stops wherever
the road takes us

04:43.883 --> 04:48.921
before reaching our final
destination, Kilauea Volcano.

04:48.955 --> 04:50.857
How high is this volcano?

04:50.890 --> 04:52.358
I don't know,
I don't know.

04:52.392 --> 04:54.861
I wonder how long ago
the last eruption was?

04:54.894 --> 04:56.696
I don't that it's --
it's running all the time,

04:56.729 --> 04:58.131
which is really cool.

04:58.164 --> 05:00.133
I can't wait.

05:00.166 --> 05:02.101
For the last 30 years,
its eruptions

05:02.135 --> 05:03.770
have been reshaping the island.

05:03.803 --> 05:06.706
It seems so untouched here.
I love it.

05:06.739 --> 05:09.709
And I've heard that the only way
to truly understand this place

05:09.742 --> 05:11.944
is to see it
with your own eyes.

05:11.978 --> 05:16.649
I love these rolling hills
that go off into the ocean.

05:16.683 --> 05:19.152
But when on a tropical island,
my first inclination

05:19.185 --> 05:21.888
is always to hit the water.

05:21.921 --> 05:24.223
Yeah, let's check it out.
Patrick?

05:24.257 --> 05:27.327
Look at that rainbow
right there.

05:27.360 --> 05:28.728
Beautiful.
<b></b>
Yeah.

05:28.761 --> 05:31.030
I've never seen one
that clear, ever.

05:32.298 --> 05:35.601
Let's get down here. I want
to see like, the full view.

05:35.635 --> 05:37.403
We got to jump
in that water.

05:37.437 --> 05:39.572
When in Hawaii...
<b></b>
Do Hawaiian stuff?

05:39.605 --> 05:42.141
Yeah.

05:45.211 --> 05:49.682
It's a double rainbow.
How pretty is this?

05:49.716 --> 05:51.918
The rainbow's
just not going away.

05:51.951 --> 05:53.119
Here, come here,
let me get a picture

05:53.152 --> 05:55.355
of you with the rainbow.

05:55.388 --> 05:58.324
I wonder if you
could swim here?

05:58.358 --> 05:59.659
Yeah.

06:00.526 --> 06:02.595
[Laughs]

06:02.628 --> 06:04.364
Reedus: Good morning.

06:04.397 --> 06:06.799
What you doing?

06:06.833 --> 06:10.670
This is like a little
homemade fish scaler.

06:10.703 --> 06:12.138
Just made out
of beer caps.

06:12.171 --> 06:13.606
That's interesting.
<b></b>
Did somebody teach you

06:13.639 --> 06:14.941
how to do that or you
just make that up?

06:14.974 --> 06:16.609
It's been around
for awhile.

06:16.642 --> 06:18.811
Pretty much, this is it.
Clean it real good.

06:18.845 --> 06:22.882
It's really pretty once
you strip its skin off.

06:22.915 --> 06:24.684
Norman.
<b></b>
Calvin.
Nice to meet you.

06:24.717 --> 06:26.552
Patrick, pleasure.
<b></b>
Nice to meet you. Yeah.

06:26.586 --> 06:28.821
What kind of fish
do you catch here?
<b></b>
All kind of reef fish.

06:28.855 --> 06:29.856
You got like,
unicorn fish.

06:29.889 --> 06:32.325
Unicorn fish?
<b></b>
Yeah.

06:32.358 --> 06:34.460
Well, that's a unicorn
fish right there.
<b></b>
Oh, these are beautiful.

06:34.494 --> 06:37.497
Oh, shut up. Unicorn fish
has a unicorn horn.

06:37.530 --> 06:39.132
Wow.
<b></b>
Do you spearfish
to catch these?

06:39.165 --> 06:41.300
Yeah, I'm a free diver,
so I don't use any tanks,

06:41.334 --> 06:42.735
I just --
I just hold my breath.

06:42.769 --> 06:44.303
How long can you
hold your breath for?

06:44.337 --> 06:46.139
Two, three minutes.
Yeah.
<b></b>
Wow.

06:46.172 --> 06:47.673
I don't think I've ever
held my breath, ever.

06:47.707 --> 06:48.975
Yeah.
<b></b>
Yeah.

06:49.008 --> 06:50.910
[Laughs]

06:50.943 --> 06:52.512
I was just going
to go do some snorkeling

06:52.545 --> 06:54.580
and I got extra gear
if you guys want to jump in.

06:54.614 --> 06:55.481
Do you wanna?
<b></b>
I'm down.

06:55.515 --> 06:57.250
Yeah.
<b></b>
Let's do it.

06:57.283 --> 06:59.185
♪♪

06:59.218 --> 07:01.554
Wait, let me --
let me fluff the package.

07:03.923 --> 07:05.825
Hey, Calvin?
You could pee in these,

07:05.858 --> 07:08.561
right, these suits?
Just in case?

07:08.594 --> 07:11.764
Yeah!

07:11.798 --> 07:14.867
[Laughs]

07:14.901 --> 07:16.736
Mmm.

07:16.769 --> 07:24.944
♪♪

07:24.977 --> 07:26.846
Calvin:
You see all those fish?
<b></b>
Yeah.

07:26.879 --> 07:28.848
You see how
big that one is?

07:28.881 --> 07:30.783
That's your parrot fish,
yeah.

07:30.817 --> 07:33.553
Let's go deeper?
Can we go deeper?

07:33.586 --> 07:43.262
♪♪

07:43.296 --> 07:45.097
Whoa, there's a whale!
Turn around!

07:45.131 --> 07:46.532
Yeah, turn
your camera around,

07:46.566 --> 07:50.203
'cause a whale jumped
out of the water.

07:50.236 --> 07:52.071
Should be right there.

07:52.104 --> 07:54.240
Giant whale came out
of the water

07:54.273 --> 07:56.476
and just went ka-plow!

07:56.509 --> 07:58.311
That was crazy.
<b></b>
That's cool, yeah.

07:58.344 --> 08:00.580
That was --
that was Dutch.

08:00.613 --> 08:02.448
If you guys want to
come up and eat fish,

08:02.482 --> 08:03.716
we're going to cook
some fish on the grill.

08:03.749 --> 08:04.817
Hell, yeah.
<b></b>
Cool.

08:04.851 --> 08:06.285
Yeah.
<b></b>
Let's do it.

08:06.319 --> 08:08.554
♪♪

08:08.588 --> 08:11.757
Yeah. We did it!

08:11.791 --> 08:13.326
Whoo!
That was dope.

08:13.359 --> 08:15.461
That whale was crazy.
<b></b>
It was huge.

08:15.495 --> 08:17.396
Yeah, it was -- I mean,
it was like, whale size,

08:17.430 --> 08:19.165
you know what I mean?

08:19.198 --> 08:21.467
The easy way is to pull down
over your elbows.

08:21.501 --> 08:28.441
♪♪

08:28.474 --> 08:31.944
That was [bleep]
awesome!

08:31.978 --> 08:33.412
Reedus:
How's it going? Hi.

08:33.446 --> 08:35.248
How was the water?
<b></b>
Oh, it was awesome.

08:35.281 --> 08:36.749
I saw a whale.

08:36.782 --> 08:38.251
There's a lot of whales
coming through now.

08:38.284 --> 08:39.919
Always in this area,
they go back

08:39.952 --> 08:41.587
to the channel
and they go to Maui.

08:41.621 --> 08:42.989
And are they protected
out here in the waters?

08:43.022 --> 08:44.290
Yes. Everything.

08:44.323 --> 08:45.625
All the whales in Hawaii
are protected.

08:45.658 --> 08:47.493
Oh, that's awesome.

08:47.527 --> 08:49.262
♪♪

08:49.295 --> 08:50.596
Reedus: It's really good.

08:50.630 --> 08:52.965
Where'd you learn
how to spearfish?

08:52.999 --> 08:55.635
I learned how to spearfish when
I was about seven years old.

08:55.668 --> 08:57.837
My grandpa used
to take me to the beach

08:57.870 --> 09:00.540
and lie down underneath a rock
and shoot fish.

09:00.573 --> 09:02.608
That's cool you have like,
memory of learning how to do it.

09:02.642 --> 09:04.343
You just got to
respect the ocean,

09:04.377 --> 09:05.611
you know,
whatever you take,

09:05.645 --> 09:07.213
you don't want
to take too much.

09:07.246 --> 09:08.814
I mean, is that like, the --
the law of the land here?

09:08.848 --> 09:10.616
Yeah.
It's basically just

09:10.650 --> 09:12.351
the whole culture thing
about Hawaii,

09:12.385 --> 09:14.487
sharing your catch,
you know.

09:14.520 --> 09:17.023
♪♪

09:17.056 --> 09:20.359
In Hawaii, we call ohana --
"ohana" means family.

09:20.393 --> 09:21.527
Nice to meet you.
Hi.

09:21.561 --> 09:23.195
In Hawaii, ohana is like --

09:23.229 --> 09:26.465
it's ohana over everything.
Family over everything.

09:26.499 --> 09:30.036
In the Hawaiian culture,
family extends past blood.

09:30.069 --> 09:32.572
Sharing everything you've got,

09:32.605 --> 09:36.309
everything you believe in,
sharing all the love.

09:36.342 --> 09:37.710
Thanks for having us.
<b></b>
A pleasure to meet you.

09:37.743 --> 09:42.048
Pleasure.
<b></b>
And everybody is one.

09:42.081 --> 09:43.683
Reedus:
This kind of inclusiveness

09:43.716 --> 09:44.984
could only could from a people

09:45.017 --> 09:46.586
isolated through much of history

09:46.619 --> 09:50.189
by thousands of miles of sea.

09:50.222 --> 09:53.826
What probably started out
as a means of survival,

09:53.859 --> 09:57.396
of man looking
after fellow man,

09:57.430 --> 09:58.831
became embedded
into their culture

09:58.864 --> 10:01.667
as an essential way of life.

10:01.701 --> 10:03.402
Reedus: Bye, whale!

10:03.436 --> 10:04.837
I've never seen
a whale that close.

10:04.870 --> 10:07.506
I've never seen a whale,
I don't think.

10:07.540 --> 10:09.408
That was nice of him.

10:09.442 --> 10:13.079
Yeah,
he was awesome, that guy.

10:13.112 --> 10:15.348
Is that snow on top
of the mountain?

10:15.381 --> 10:17.717
Oh, yeah, you can see
snow right there, dude.

10:17.750 --> 10:20.753
It's such a contradiction
down here and up there.

10:20.786 --> 10:22.254
It keeps shifting
from like,

10:22.288 --> 10:25.191
"Lost in Space,"
to an American western.

10:25.224 --> 10:27.093
Yeah, I didn't expect Hawaii
to look like this at all.

10:27.126 --> 10:29.195
I mean, they've got
a lot of everything here.

10:29.228 --> 10:30.863
Wild goats.

10:30.896 --> 10:33.866
[Motorcycle horn honks]
<b></b>
[Laughs]

10:33.899 --> 10:36.268
Part of any ride
is the hunt for authenticity,

10:36.302 --> 10:38.270
finding the little things
that make a place

10:38.304 --> 10:40.706
all its own and in Hawaii,

10:40.740 --> 10:42.074
that means coffee.

10:42.108 --> 10:43.809
Of the 50 states,
it's the only one

10:43.843 --> 10:46.412
producing my main caffeine fix.

10:46.445 --> 10:48.280
So we're heading to a spot
I've heard serves

10:48.314 --> 10:50.816
the best cup of coffee
on the island.

10:50.850 --> 10:54.053
I'm excited.
I'm a coffee enthusiast.

10:54.086 --> 10:56.489
You are definitely
a coffee junkie.

10:56.522 --> 10:59.058
Whenever I go to L. A.
and I hang out with you,

10:59.091 --> 11:01.560
I probably drink 10 cups
of coffee a day.

11:01.594 --> 11:03.896
I hope it's like,
super-dark roast.

11:03.929 --> 11:05.631
I don't know, I'm excited
to find out, though.

11:05.665 --> 11:07.900
I brought a thermos,
I'm going to fill it up.

11:07.933 --> 11:10.603
But first, a quick pit stop.

11:10.636 --> 11:12.505
Yo, Patrick,
you need to stop?

11:12.538 --> 11:14.173
We're going to stop
at this pink hotel.

11:14.206 --> 11:16.008
Yeah, let's go.

11:16.042 --> 11:21.814
♪♪

11:21.847 --> 11:23.916
Yeah,
this is real pink.

11:23.949 --> 11:25.584
This is pinky pink.

11:25.618 --> 11:27.820
Hi.
<b></b>
Woman: Aloha.

11:27.853 --> 11:29.622
Aloha.
<b></b>
Hi. How are you?

11:29.655 --> 11:31.957
Can we use your bathroom
real quick?
<b></b>
Yeah, of course.

11:31.991 --> 11:33.592
We have a great
bathroom out back.

11:33.626 --> 11:36.262
Great.
Let's go see it.
<b></b>
[Bell rings]

11:36.295 --> 11:37.596
Look at this.

11:37.630 --> 11:40.032
Hoelck:
Oh, my goodness.

11:40.066 --> 11:42.435
Oh, this is great.
Look at -- look at this.

11:42.468 --> 11:44.470
Go in there.

11:45.304 --> 11:50.643
Crazy, right? This is kind
of like, the best pit stop ever.

11:50.676 --> 11:52.545
Do you feel more
connected to nature now?

11:52.578 --> 11:54.013
A little bit.

11:54.046 --> 11:55.681
[Urinating]

11:55.715 --> 11:57.283
I can hear you peeing,
by the way.

11:57.316 --> 11:59.518
How does it sound?
<b></b>
It sounds like you're peeing.

11:59.552 --> 12:01.821
[Chuckles]

12:01.854 --> 12:03.656
♪♪

12:03.689 --> 12:05.991
Are you still peeing?
<b></b>
I'm done.

12:06.025 --> 12:08.461
[Toilet flushes]

12:10.396 --> 12:12.865
Listen how far down it goes.

12:12.898 --> 12:16.135
[Toilet flushing]

12:16.168 --> 12:19.038
Ha.

12:19.071 --> 12:21.874
Well worth the wait.

12:21.907 --> 12:23.409
Reedus: Thanks so much
for letting us come in.

12:23.442 --> 12:25.544
Woman: Oh, thank you.
<b></b>
What's going on right here?

12:25.578 --> 12:28.914
1910?
<b></b>
This is Mr. Inaba's
parents,

12:28.948 --> 12:30.983
who actually
started the hotel.

12:31.016 --> 12:33.085
Is this one of those old photos
that you had to sit

12:33.119 --> 12:34.587
for an hour
to get the photo?

12:34.620 --> 12:35.988
[Laughter]

12:36.021 --> 12:37.656
Look at these old cars,
too.

12:37.690 --> 12:38.924
Has the bathroom
always been

12:38.958 --> 12:40.860
that scenic bathroom?
It has been.

12:40.893 --> 12:42.661
It was actually a dry toilet,
back in the day,

12:42.695 --> 12:44.330
before they even had
running water.

12:44.363 --> 12:46.332
So they've decided to just
keep it as a bathroom

12:46.365 --> 12:50.102
and it's been the talk of
the town ever since.

12:50.136 --> 12:52.938
I'm glad you men were able
to stop by and use our bathroom.

12:52.972 --> 12:53.906
[Laughing]

12:53.939 --> 12:55.274
You're so sweet.

12:55.307 --> 12:57.276
Later, gator.
Later, gator.

12:57.309 --> 12:58.677
Good job.
Thank you.

12:58.711 --> 13:00.513
Y'all have a safe ride.
<b></b>
Thank you.

13:00.546 --> 13:03.048
[Motorcycle engine starts]

13:03.616 --> 13:06.185
♪♪

13:06.218 --> 13:08.187
What'd you think
of the pink hotel?

13:08.220 --> 13:11.891
I liked it.
I liked peeing there.

13:11.924 --> 13:14.760
[Laughs] I wish the urinal
had a better view.

13:14.794 --> 13:17.062
This whole day
has been a pee pee party.

13:17.096 --> 13:20.032
As my buddy Negan would say,
it was a "pee pee pants party."

13:20.065 --> 13:21.467
[Laughs]

13:21.500 --> 13:24.136
Bada-baba.

13:24.170 --> 13:26.806
Reedus: This is unreal.

13:26.839 --> 13:28.207
[Cows mooing]

13:28.240 --> 13:30.609
[Laughs]
<b></b>
Whoo!

13:30.643 --> 13:32.444
Jessica: It's actually
the home of Pele,

13:32.478 --> 13:33.779
our Hawaiian
volcano goddess.

13:33.813 --> 13:35.381
I feel like I would have
a crush on Pele

13:35.414 --> 13:37.183
and then she would
turn me into a tree.

13:40.019 --> 13:40.186
[Birds

13:40.186 --> 13:41.654
[Birds singing]

13:41.687 --> 13:43.122
[Birds singing]

13:43.155 --> 13:50.229
♪♪

13:50.262 --> 13:51.964
[Truck horn honking]

13:51.997 --> 13:54.967
♪♪

13:55.000 --> 13:57.703
Ah!

13:57.736 --> 14:00.906
Yeah!

14:00.940 --> 14:04.810
This is so cool.
There's all this mountain vibe.

14:04.844 --> 14:06.245
The colors are extreme,
right?

14:06.278 --> 14:09.882
Yeah.
<b></b>
Smells good.

14:09.915 --> 14:11.750
It does smell good.

14:11.784 --> 14:14.386
Coffee!
Coffee, coffee!

14:14.420 --> 14:17.756
Reedus: 300 years ago, the first
Westerners showed up on Hawaii,

14:17.790 --> 14:22.261
bringing along agricultural
staples from the mainland.

14:22.294 --> 14:24.897
Soon, Hawaiian cowboys
and coffee farmers

14:24.930 --> 14:26.565
took over the countryside,

14:26.599 --> 14:29.401
transforming the island forever.

14:29.435 --> 14:33.105
Leaving Holualoa, it's
a 70-mile coastline ride

14:33.138 --> 14:35.741
around the island's
southern tip into Pahala,

14:35.774 --> 14:38.677
where we reach
Aikane Plantation.

14:38.711 --> 14:42.181
It's a working ranch
and a coffee farm, all in one.

14:48.387 --> 14:50.689
Hi. I'm Meryl.
<b></b>
Hi.

14:50.723 --> 14:52.024
Nice to meet you, Norman.
<b></b>
Nice to meet you, yeah.

14:52.057 --> 14:53.459
Nice to meet you.
<b></b>
Hi, nice to meet you.

14:53.492 --> 14:55.728
Pleasure.
<b></b>
Please,
come help yourself.

14:55.761 --> 14:57.763
Yeah?
Do you drink so much coffee,

14:57.796 --> 14:59.398
having your own
coffee spot?

14:59.431 --> 15:00.633
No, I try not to.

15:00.666 --> 15:02.067
I'd be like, ay-yi-yi-yi,
all the time.

15:02.101 --> 15:04.436
Yeah. [Laughs]
<b></b>
I would.

15:04.470 --> 15:06.038
My grandfather
was a rancher,

15:06.071 --> 15:09.975
but my great-grandfather
was the coffee grower.

15:10.009 --> 15:14.613
And he was the first coffee
grower in this district.

15:14.647 --> 15:17.917
This has been in my family
since the 1800s.

15:17.950 --> 15:19.151
Wow.
Yeah.

15:19.184 --> 15:20.152
This is delicious.

15:20.185 --> 15:21.220
Yeah.
<b></b>
Mm-hmm.

15:21.253 --> 15:23.188
I'm moving in.
<b></b>
[Laughs]

15:24.356 --> 15:28.093
[Horn blowing]

15:28.127 --> 15:30.629
What's happening?
<b></b>
That's protocol,

15:30.663 --> 15:34.500
announcing that we're going up
into the mountain area

15:34.533 --> 15:38.470
and we don't mean
any harm to the mountain.

15:38.504 --> 15:41.607
[Blows horn]

15:47.012 --> 15:51.350
[Blows horn]

15:51.383 --> 15:52.651
That was beautiful.

15:52.685 --> 15:54.820
Are we ready to
go see some cows?

15:54.853 --> 15:56.455
You give us coffee
and then put us to work.

15:56.488 --> 15:57.856
Is that how it works?
<b></b>
That's right.

15:57.890 --> 15:59.325
[Laughter]
<b></b>
Let's do it.

15:59.358 --> 16:02.494
Hoelck: Am I driving?
<b></b>
Yeah.

16:02.528 --> 16:04.096
Patrick, we're friends,
drive nicely.

16:04.129 --> 16:05.965
I'm going to go nice.

16:05.998 --> 16:08.500
♪♪

16:08.534 --> 16:10.602
Come down, come!

16:13.973 --> 16:16.108
Coming up
over the mountain.

16:16.141 --> 16:18.277
Yo!

16:18.310 --> 16:20.646
And the bull's
in the lead.

16:20.679 --> 16:23.215
♪♪

16:23.248 --> 16:25.284
Come, come,
come, come!

16:25.317 --> 16:27.820
There's some that don't want
to go through that gate.

16:27.853 --> 16:29.722
Come!
<b></b>
[Smacking lips]

16:29.755 --> 16:32.057
Come on.
<b></b>
I think we can
stop up here.

16:32.091 --> 16:33.993
Oh, here we go.

16:34.026 --> 16:35.861
Come on, I got lunch.

16:35.894 --> 16:37.629
You are so slimy.

16:37.663 --> 16:39.732
Uhh!

16:39.765 --> 16:41.200
[Smack lips]

16:41.233 --> 16:42.868
Over here!

16:42.901 --> 16:44.536
There's a -- there's a --
there's a fly problem.

16:44.570 --> 16:46.238
We got a fly problem.

16:46.271 --> 16:49.842
Ugh.
Ugh.

16:49.875 --> 16:51.810
You are super-gross.

16:51.844 --> 16:55.914
Ugh.
Whoo-hoo-hoo!

16:55.948 --> 16:58.817
Ooh, hi.

16:58.851 --> 17:00.185
Oh, yes, over here.

17:00.219 --> 17:01.854
[Cow mooing]

17:01.887 --> 17:04.323
Yeah, so this right here --
<b></b>
Oh, he licked my --

17:04.356 --> 17:06.892
-- nothing like playing
a cowboy in the movies.

17:06.925 --> 17:09.261
I have cow slime
all over my pants.

17:09.294 --> 17:11.497
Meryl: [Laughs]

17:11.530 --> 17:15.267
♪♪

17:15.300 --> 17:17.069
This is my ohana.

17:17.102 --> 17:18.704
They're friends
that have been

17:18.737 --> 17:21.673
in the area
for a long time.

17:21.707 --> 17:23.175
[Singing in native language]
<b></b>
This is a feast right here.

17:23.208 --> 17:25.444
Growing up in Hawaii,
you go to a luau.

17:25.477 --> 17:27.279
That's a big party
and family comes

17:27.312 --> 17:29.848
with guitars, ukuleles.

17:29.882 --> 17:33.285
A lot of times, it's to pay back
all your workers.

17:33.318 --> 17:34.853
It's saying thank you,

17:34.887 --> 17:38.123
saying mahalo for all
the work that was done.

17:38.157 --> 17:39.792
Reedus:
[Sucking fingers]

17:39.825 --> 17:42.294
They don't mess around.
<b></b>
Mnh-Mnh.

17:42.327 --> 17:43.529
You're good on a horse.

17:43.562 --> 17:44.797
Oh, thank you.
<b></b>
Yeah.

17:44.830 --> 17:46.231
Did you ever
ride motorcycles?

17:46.265 --> 17:48.233
No, I'm scared.
<b></b>
Really?

17:48.267 --> 17:50.969
But you ride the black stallion
like it's nothing.

17:51.003 --> 17:52.404
You could ride a bike.

17:52.438 --> 17:54.073
Reedus: Today, we caught
a glimpse of Hawaii

17:54.106 --> 17:55.908
that I didn't even know existed

17:55.941 --> 17:58.077
and that alone made it
worth the journey.

17:58.110 --> 17:59.711
This is a great
time here.

17:59.745 --> 18:01.046
Thank you so much.
<b></b>
Thanks for having us.

18:01.080 --> 18:02.881
I'm not usually one
to eat and run,

18:02.915 --> 18:03.982
but it's been a long day.

18:04.016 --> 18:05.250
Bye, cutie.
<b></b>
Bye-bye.

18:05.284 --> 18:06.919
And after all that
cattle slobber --

18:06.952 --> 18:08.554
Oh, wait, wait, wait,
I got to get my coffee to go.

18:08.587 --> 18:11.256
-- I think a hot bath
might just be in my future.

18:11.290 --> 18:13.058
Bye, guys!

18:14.660 --> 18:16.995
♪♪

18:17.029 --> 18:19.331
Morning.

18:19.364 --> 18:22.067
My phone, grab my change,
got the camera.

18:22.101 --> 18:24.970
I got my dad's
lucky belt buckle. See that?

18:25.003 --> 18:26.905
That used to be
my dad's belt buckle.

18:26.939 --> 18:29.908
And the back says, "1939."

18:29.942 --> 18:33.112
Dad for luck. Cool.
Let's do it.

18:33.145 --> 18:34.947
♪♪

18:34.980 --> 18:38.183
Whoo!
<b></b>
Quick, close your eyes
and picture Hawaii.

18:38.217 --> 18:39.618
What do you see?

18:39.651 --> 18:42.187
Probably not this.
<b></b>
Chickens.

18:42.221 --> 18:43.755
What's up, chickens?

18:43.789 --> 18:45.424
But on the Big Island,

18:45.457 --> 18:47.793
even with its miles
of barren landscape,

18:47.826 --> 18:50.162
beauty is all around.

18:50.195 --> 18:53.198
Flamingo.
[Laughs]

18:53.232 --> 18:55.467
You just need to know
where to look.

18:55.501 --> 18:56.835
That's so purple.

18:56.869 --> 18:58.837
That's the best part
about bikes is like,

18:58.871 --> 19:00.672
you can't text
and you can't look

19:00.706 --> 19:03.375
at some stupid
scroll on Instagram.

19:03.408 --> 19:05.377
That's so true.
<b></b>
Patrick's heard about one

19:05.410 --> 19:07.279
of the most
picturesque spots here,

19:07.312 --> 19:08.380
so we're going
to go start our day

19:08.413 --> 19:11.350
by checking it out.

19:11.383 --> 19:14.353
[Animal howling]

19:16.889 --> 19:18.323
Hi.

19:18.357 --> 19:20.526
You smell that nature.

19:20.559 --> 19:22.361
Good morning. Hey.
<b></b>
How are you?

19:25.831 --> 19:27.132
Yeah.
<b></b>
[Laughs]

19:27.166 --> 19:28.467
Reedus: It's crazy with
all this jungle

19:28.500 --> 19:30.969
that they don't have
any poisonous snakes.

19:31.003 --> 19:33.305
There's like no monkeys
or anything, right?

19:33.338 --> 19:34.907
No.
<b></b>
Like,
if this was Costa Rica,

19:34.940 --> 19:36.975
it'd be,
pow-pow-pow-pow-pow-pow!

19:37.009 --> 19:39.077
♪♪

19:39.111 --> 19:41.346
Is that the waterfall?

19:41.380 --> 19:43.182
Whoa.

19:43.215 --> 19:44.816
That's just stupid.

19:44.850 --> 19:46.318
Right?
<b></b>
Yes.

19:46.351 --> 19:49.821
That is just
stupid-pretty.

19:49.855 --> 19:52.157
You know what this is?

19:52.191 --> 19:54.092
What?
<b></b>
Paradise.

19:54.126 --> 19:57.930
♪♪

19:57.963 --> 20:00.365
I'm going to do
the pano real quick.

20:00.399 --> 20:03.735
[Cellphone beeps]

20:03.769 --> 20:05.771
I suck at panos.
You know what I mean?

20:05.804 --> 20:07.339
Like, I suck
at the panorama.

20:07.372 --> 20:09.575
Derba-derba-derba-deb,
you know?

20:09.608 --> 20:12.611
[Laughs]

20:12.644 --> 20:14.346
Oh, wow,
look at this tree.

20:14.379 --> 20:16.381
I've never seen
a tree like this.

20:16.415 --> 20:18.350
This tree here
is a banyan tree.

20:18.383 --> 20:20.085
It grows these aerial roots

20:20.118 --> 20:21.587
and when they touch the ground,

20:21.620 --> 20:23.055
they just form another trunk.

20:23.088 --> 20:24.690
Did the
lava come through here

20:24.723 --> 20:26.925
and take these out,
back in the day?

20:26.959 --> 20:30.128
The lava
won't come here.

20:30.162 --> 20:32.097
There's a legend
about the fire god,

20:32.130 --> 20:35.067
Pele and her
boyfriend Kamapua'a.

20:35.100 --> 20:37.269
They were like lovers,
but then they fought.

20:37.302 --> 20:41.607
She said, you live from
Wailuku River to the north

20:41.640 --> 20:44.977
and I'll stay from
Wailuku River, east to south.

20:45.010 --> 20:47.579
So that's why
when she pass a river,

20:47.613 --> 20:50.749
you start seeing
lava flows, lava rocks.

20:50.782 --> 20:54.086
Pele is an ancient
Hawaiian goddess

20:54.119 --> 20:56.989
that pretty much created
all the islands.

20:57.022 --> 21:00.726
♪♪

21:00.759 --> 21:02.661
Is -- what does she look like?
Is there any like,

21:02.694 --> 21:03.962
visions of what she's
supposed to look like?

21:03.996 --> 21:06.164
There's various
interpretations.

21:06.198 --> 21:08.100
Old woman with long,
gray hair.

21:08.133 --> 21:10.269
I thought she would be
a redhead, for sure.

21:10.302 --> 21:12.738
♪♪

21:12.771 --> 21:14.006
Woman: She's beautiful.

21:14.039 --> 21:16.508
She's normally
dressed in white,

21:16.541 --> 21:17.943
from what I understand.

21:17.976 --> 21:20.178
Man: She's a walking
lava goddess.

21:20.212 --> 21:22.781
You respect her,
she'll respect us.

21:22.814 --> 21:25.317
Creates, as well
as takes away, huh?
<b></b>
Yeah.

21:25.350 --> 21:27.252
You don't mess with her.
<b></b>
No, you don't mess with her.

21:27.286 --> 21:29.054
Yeah.

21:30.455 --> 21:32.691
I like your shirt.
<b></b>
Can we have one
more picture?

21:32.724 --> 21:34.159
Oh, listen, lady...

21:34.192 --> 21:37.429
Please? Please?
<b></b>
[Laughter]

21:37.462 --> 21:39.931
♪♪

21:39.965 --> 21:41.867
This one had a few drinks
this morning.

21:41.900 --> 21:44.169
[Laughs]

21:44.202 --> 21:46.171
Thank you!
<b></b>
Of course, yeah.

21:46.204 --> 21:48.840
Reedus: Give me whatever
she's having.

21:48.874 --> 21:51.476
On second thought,
scratch that.

21:51.510 --> 21:53.011
♪♪

21:53.045 --> 21:55.113
We're off to see a group
whose respect for Pele

21:55.147 --> 21:58.450
and her creations is evident
in how they ride.

21:58.483 --> 22:00.952
Reedus:
Rock Island Riders.

22:00.986 --> 22:03.455
Hoelck: I can't wait.

22:03.488 --> 22:05.057
Look at all these hoodlums.

22:05.090 --> 22:07.225
If we could get a permit,
we could ride over the lava.

22:07.259 --> 22:08.794
Why do I think
you're messing with me?

22:08.827 --> 22:10.862
I mean, right?
He's just got that face.

22:13.932 --> 22:16.735
Reedus:
I had this lady come up to me
the other day and she's like,

22:16.768 --> 22:18.203
"Oh, my God,
I watched your show.

22:18.236 --> 22:19.871
It was so depressing,"
and I'm like, "Yeah, yeah."

22:19.905 --> 22:24.343
She's like, "Sean Penn was
the rapist, molester, whatever,"

22:24.376 --> 22:26.144
and I'm like,
"That's not my show."
<b></b>
[Laughs]

22:26.178 --> 22:28.013
She's like,
"Yeah, the 'Dead' thing."

22:28.046 --> 22:29.681
They know
that you're famous,

22:29.715 --> 22:32.017
but they don't know
what it is.

22:33.585 --> 22:36.388
Reedus: Leaving Honomu,
we're taking a 20-mile ride

22:36.421 --> 22:38.423
down the Mamalahoa Highway

22:38.457 --> 22:40.592
to meet up with
a dual sport biker group

22:40.625 --> 22:43.195
who knows the best way
to experience this island

22:43.228 --> 22:46.098
is to leave
the roads behind.

22:46.131 --> 22:47.866
Don't you have
another dirt bike?

22:47.899 --> 22:50.736
Yeah, I'm really liking
the enduro, though,

22:50.769 --> 22:52.904
because it's just
so light and fun.

22:52.938 --> 22:56.775
It's kind of like a regression,
because I used to do motorcross.

22:56.808 --> 22:59.311
When I was a kid,
that's how it all started.

23:01.446 --> 23:03.181
This must be the place.

23:06.084 --> 23:07.953
Reedus: Look at all
these hoodlums.

23:07.986 --> 23:10.455
You look like a hoodlum.
<b></b>
I know, I'm the worst
one and trust me.

23:10.489 --> 23:11.923
How are you, man? Norman.
<b></b>
Steve.

23:11.957 --> 23:13.625
Nice to meet you, brother.
What's up, man?

23:13.658 --> 23:14.960
How are you?
<b></b>
Norman.
Nice to meet you.

23:14.993 --> 23:17.062
Good to meet you.

23:17.095 --> 23:19.698
This looks like a --
a guy's wet dream.

23:19.731 --> 23:21.400
[Laughter]

23:21.433 --> 23:22.601
Man and his toys,
huh?

23:22.634 --> 23:23.969
You got everything in here.

23:24.002 --> 23:26.405
Oh, yeah.
<b></b>
How was your ride so far?

23:26.438 --> 23:28.373
It's been beautiful.
It's so pretty here.

23:28.407 --> 23:31.309
Yeah, this island is a favorite
for all motorcycle riders,

23:31.343 --> 23:32.744
because this is
a volcanic island,

23:32.778 --> 23:34.079
you know, so,
and it's still going.

23:34.112 --> 23:35.714
How close can you get to it?

23:35.747 --> 23:37.883
If we could get a permit,
we could ride over the lava,

23:37.916 --> 23:39.217
which we used to do
in the old days.

23:39.251 --> 23:40.919
That doesn't rip your tires?
It does.

23:40.952 --> 23:42.154
Oh, it does?
<b></b>
Eats it.

23:42.187 --> 23:43.255
You can burn up
a set of tires

23:43.288 --> 23:44.623
in one day
on that stuff.

23:44.656 --> 23:45.924
Like a dangerous
crew right here.

23:45.957 --> 23:47.325
I can feel it.

23:47.359 --> 23:48.994
[Laughter]

23:49.027 --> 23:50.395
♪♪

23:50.429 --> 23:51.730
Steve:
We do off-road only.

23:51.763 --> 23:53.465
Yeah, that's kind
of his forte as well.

23:53.498 --> 23:55.400
Really?
<b></b>
Yes. Sunset Boulevard.

23:55.434 --> 23:58.069
[Laughter]
<b></b>
Right?

23:58.103 --> 24:01.640
We used to do a --
a 200-mile enduro

24:01.673 --> 24:04.309
on this island.

24:04.342 --> 24:06.111
Narrator:
The terrain is so varied,

24:06.144 --> 24:08.513
the weather so different
from point to point,

24:08.547 --> 24:12.918
that the Mauna Kea 200
is truly a ride to remember.

24:12.951 --> 24:15.153
We -- we quit it about,
a few years ago,

24:15.187 --> 24:17.489
just because getting permits
was too much of a pain.

24:17.522 --> 24:20.158
There's all kinds
of close calls, you know.

24:20.192 --> 24:22.627
Cars coming your way
when we're off-roading

24:22.661 --> 24:25.163
and cows going in --
in your path and --

24:25.197 --> 24:26.865
A cow?
<b></b>
Yeah.

24:26.898 --> 24:30.435
So coming home in one piece is
really the most important thing.

24:30.469 --> 24:31.870
So we're going to get
something to eat.

24:31.903 --> 24:33.772
Oh, yeah.
<b></b>
Oh, yeah, sounds good.

24:33.805 --> 24:35.640
[Dirt bike engines revving ]

24:39.077 --> 24:41.446
♪♪

24:41.480 --> 24:43.048
Reedus: All right!
This is awesome.

24:43.081 --> 24:44.983
I feel like we're going
to go rob a bank.

24:45.016 --> 24:46.318
[Laughs]

24:46.351 --> 24:47.819
Steve: Beautiful day.

24:47.853 --> 24:50.355
I see some gray clouds
up ahead, though.

24:50.388 --> 24:52.791
Well, some of that might be the
fall from the volcanoes, so...

24:52.824 --> 24:54.559
That's volcano
smoke over there?

24:54.593 --> 24:56.361
That's volcano smoke,
yes, sir.

24:56.394 --> 24:57.829
Wow.
<b></b>
[Dog barking]

24:57.863 --> 24:59.464
[ Laughs ]

24:59.498 --> 25:02.467
Cujo!

25:02.501 --> 25:04.703
We're entering Old
Historic Hilo.

25:04.736 --> 25:06.671
♪♪

25:06.705 --> 25:08.673
Look at this.
This is beautiful.

25:08.707 --> 25:10.675
Wow.

25:10.709 --> 25:13.979
This is Honoli'i,
a local surfing beach.

25:14.012 --> 25:18.016
Wow.
That's a real wave.

25:18.049 --> 25:20.485
This town has been hit
by tidal waves twice.

25:20.519 --> 25:21.920
Really?
<b></b>
The whole town is --

25:21.953 --> 25:23.355
was wiped out.
Yeah.

25:23.388 --> 25:25.223
That's why,
if you look on the horizon,

25:25.257 --> 25:26.691
you see the break
wall out there.

25:26.725 --> 25:28.827
That could stop tidal waves?
<b></b>
Actually, it does.

25:28.860 --> 25:31.530
If -- if the wave's coming in,
it breaks the wave.

25:31.563 --> 25:34.933
This place is fully
alive all the time.

25:34.966 --> 25:37.736
This is the Old
Mamalahoa Highway.

25:39.404 --> 25:41.606
Oh, wow.
<b></b>
You can just
imagine driving

25:41.640 --> 25:43.742
all the way
to Kona on this road.

25:43.775 --> 25:45.544
It'd take you all day
to get there.

25:45.577 --> 25:47.746
Wow, look at this.
Beautiful.

25:47.779 --> 25:49.080
Reedus: Making our way
through this narrow,

25:49.114 --> 25:50.715
twisted, old highway,

25:50.749 --> 25:52.784
it's as if it were made
with a motorcycle in mind.

25:52.817 --> 25:55.086
Look at that bamboo.
Look how tall that is.

25:55.120 --> 25:56.721
Steve: Everything
gets big in Hawaii.

25:56.755 --> 26:00.191
The towering trees,
the lush tropical air,

26:00.225 --> 26:04.629
you're totally encompassed
by your surroundings.

26:04.663 --> 26:07.532
Hoelck:
This is awesome, man.

26:07.566 --> 26:09.334
Yeah.

26:12.103 --> 26:13.805
Steve: Okay.
<b></b>
Reedus:
All right, let's go.

26:13.838 --> 26:16.241
Poi. Let's see if we can find
some poi, too, okay.

26:16.274 --> 26:18.610
♪♪

26:18.643 --> 26:21.212
Oh, this is all
fresh stuff.

26:21.246 --> 26:23.448
Hi.
<b></b>
How are you?

26:23.481 --> 26:26.318
Oh, gosh!
<b></b>
[Laughter]

26:26.351 --> 26:28.153
What was I getting?
<b></b>
Poi.

26:28.186 --> 26:30.322
Poi.
<b></b>
Poi and poke.

26:30.355 --> 26:32.657
Okay.
<b></b>
Why do I think
you're messing with me?

26:32.691 --> 26:34.492
I mean, right?
He's just got that face.

26:34.526 --> 26:38.463
Like he's trying to trick me
into eating something gnarly.

26:38.496 --> 26:40.098
Is this us?
<b></b>
Yes.

26:40.131 --> 26:41.633
And then what do I
do with that?

26:41.666 --> 26:44.803
You dip your poke in it
and you eat it.

26:44.836 --> 26:47.272
Dip?
<b></b>
You sure?

26:47.305 --> 26:48.473
Yes.

26:48.506 --> 26:50.775
Bye, thank you.
<b></b>
Have a nice day.

26:50.809 --> 26:52.844
We stole all this food.
We're not paying.

26:52.877 --> 26:54.279
You'll never catch us.

26:54.312 --> 26:56.414
[Laughs]

26:56.448 --> 26:59.651
Wow,
this is so pretty here.

26:59.684 --> 27:02.187
Where's your poi?
Where's your poi?

27:02.220 --> 27:05.624
Poi is the staple food
of the ancient Hawaiians.

27:05.657 --> 27:06.925
Hoelck:
What is it made out of?

27:06.958 --> 27:08.026
Steve: It's taro.

27:08.059 --> 27:09.327
It's a taro plant

27:09.361 --> 27:11.930
that we squash
and we smash,

27:11.963 --> 27:14.332
turns to like, putty.
<b></b>
Take a stab.

27:14.366 --> 27:16.668
My children,
they ate poi

27:16.701 --> 27:19.137
before they even ate baby food.

27:19.170 --> 27:23.375
♪♪

27:23.408 --> 27:26.845
[Laughs]

27:26.878 --> 27:28.213
It doesn't taste
like nothing.

27:28.246 --> 27:30.181
Yeah.
<b></b>
There's no flavor
to that.

27:30.215 --> 27:32.350
Tastes like dirt.
<b></b>
[Laughter]

27:32.384 --> 27:33.818
Right here.

27:33.852 --> 27:36.021
The real Hawaiians actually
like it when it starts

27:36.054 --> 27:38.056
actually growing green stuff
on the top of it.

27:38.089 --> 27:40.458
Oh, like fungus
and mold.
<b></b>
Yeah.

27:40.492 --> 27:42.193
I lived in Japan
for awhile.
<b></b>
Oh?

27:42.227 --> 27:44.529
I've had some funky food
in Japan, I'll tell you that.

27:44.562 --> 27:46.031
Yeah. There's
some things in Georgia you

27:46.064 --> 27:47.032
don't want to eat, too.

27:47.065 --> 27:49.200
[Laughter]

27:49.234 --> 27:51.002
Mm.
You guys are great

27:51.036 --> 27:52.671
at protecting things here.

27:52.704 --> 27:54.806
Well, it comes --
comes down from the Hawaiians.

27:54.839 --> 27:56.207
'Cause the population
of the Big Island

27:56.241 --> 27:58.376
used to be like
250,000 people before.

27:58.410 --> 28:00.745
Really?
<b></b>
Way more
than it is now.

28:00.779 --> 28:02.480
This was pre-Western
contact.

28:02.514 --> 28:05.016
And all of those people had to
be supported off the land, so...

28:05.050 --> 28:06.317
Why has it changed
to where there's

28:06.351 --> 28:07.852
less people
on the Big Island?

28:07.886 --> 28:11.523
Well, when Western people
started coming here,

28:11.556 --> 28:13.692
they brought diseases
with 'em.
<b></b>
Oh, wow.

28:13.725 --> 28:15.560
And so the Hawaiian
population died out.

28:15.593 --> 28:17.362
Wow.
I didn't know any of this.

28:17.395 --> 28:19.998
I didn't know that,
either.
Yeah.

28:20.031 --> 28:22.333
Steve: Anybody like some poi?
Norman, you don't like poi?

28:22.367 --> 28:24.335
You know, I'm kind of
on the fence with the poi,

28:24.369 --> 28:25.737
I got to tell you.

28:25.770 --> 28:28.239
[Laughter]

28:28.273 --> 28:30.442
Thank you guys for
taking us on this journey.

28:30.475 --> 28:32.577
You guys are awesome.
Yeah.

28:32.610 --> 28:35.447
The Rock Island Riders
aren't your typical biker group,

28:35.480 --> 28:37.749
but after two days
on the Big Island,

28:37.782 --> 28:40.685
I'm realizing this place
is full of surprises.

28:40.719 --> 28:43.254
How amazing.
<b></b>
This is beautiful
right here.

28:43.288 --> 28:53.264
♪♪

28:53.298 --> 28:54.866
Reedus:
We can sit here.

28:54.899 --> 28:57.035
Hoelck: Look,
they have a koi farm.

28:57.068 --> 28:59.070
I like that there's a group
like those guys, like --

28:59.104 --> 29:00.572
They were the coolest.

29:00.605 --> 29:02.107
They're like, older and they're
like still doing it.

29:02.140 --> 29:03.742
And they're good people.
<b></b>
Yeah.

29:03.775 --> 29:04.976
You think you could
ever live here,

29:05.009 --> 29:06.277
like, does it
drive you nuts --?

29:06.311 --> 29:07.879
Full-time, no?
<b></b>
Don't you get tired of L.A.,

29:07.912 --> 29:09.481
though, after awhile?
I get tired

29:09.514 --> 29:10.949
of wherever after awhile

29:10.982 --> 29:12.217
and want to just pick up
everything and move.

29:12.250 --> 29:13.818
Yeah. Yeah.
If I didn't have

29:13.852 --> 29:15.553
the job I have in L.A.,
the life I have,

29:15.587 --> 29:17.322
I'd probably be
very different about it.

29:17.355 --> 29:18.623
Yeah.

29:18.656 --> 29:20.225
I've heard paradise
isn't a place,

29:20.258 --> 29:21.826
but a state of mind.

29:21.860 --> 29:25.330
Whoever said that obviously
never made it to Hawaii.

29:25.363 --> 29:27.165
What -- what are we doing
tomorrow, by the way?

29:27.198 --> 29:28.633
Everything.

29:28.666 --> 29:29.834
♪♪

29:29.868 --> 29:31.402
Timber! Watch out!
Banana!

29:31.436 --> 29:32.937
Yeah!

29:32.971 --> 29:35.940
The lava itself is about
75 feet below the surface.

29:40.211 --> 29:42.747
Reedus: Oh, my God.
There's a pig.

29:42.781 --> 29:44.182
Are we breaking
in someone's house right now?

29:44.215 --> 29:45.850
Yeah.

29:45.884 --> 29:48.052
Oh, my God! Hi.
<b></b>
Don't let him out.

29:48.086 --> 29:49.287
Come here.
<b></b>
[Pig oinks]

29:49.320 --> 29:51.523
Oh. Oh.

29:51.556 --> 29:53.224
Oh.
He's feisty, come here.

29:53.258 --> 29:55.794
No, no, he's like biting
at me.
<b></b>
Hey, come here.

29:55.827 --> 29:58.296
Hi.
Hi.

29:58.329 --> 29:59.764
Ow! He bit me!
<b></b>
[Laughs]

29:59.798 --> 30:01.432
Man: This is Humphrey.

30:01.466 --> 30:03.034
He was on the beach

30:03.067 --> 30:04.702
all by himself,
about a week old.

30:04.736 --> 30:06.304
He's about four months now.

30:06.337 --> 30:08.139
Does he bite you?
<b></b>
Yeah, he bit me.

30:08.173 --> 30:09.874
He's teething.

30:09.908 --> 30:11.876
It's interesting he doesn't
freak out on you.

30:11.910 --> 30:14.579
He knows it's you, right?
<b></b>
Yeah, he sleeps with me.

30:14.612 --> 30:16.915
He matches your outfit.
<b></b>
Ow! He bit me again.

30:16.948 --> 30:18.383
I could see you
with one of these.

30:18.416 --> 30:19.984
Yeah, right, my cat
would kill this thing.

30:20.018 --> 30:22.287
[Pig squeals]

30:22.320 --> 30:23.822
That's what I sound
like when I wake up.

30:23.855 --> 30:24.789
Oink, oink,
oink, oink.

30:28.326 --> 30:30.361
Reedus: So thi
cool little area, right?

30:30.395 --> 30:32.964
Yeah, it's very --
it's like a western town.

30:32.997 --> 30:34.966
[Laughs]

30:34.999 --> 30:37.135
What's up, man?
<b></b>
Reedus: Last night,
we caught some zzz's

30:37.168 --> 30:38.770
in the coastal town of Hilo.

30:39.971 --> 30:42.874
Oh, my God!
<b></b>
What's popping, baby?

30:42.907 --> 30:45.143
Can I get a picture
with you, man?
<b></b>
Of course, yeah.

30:45.176 --> 30:48.112
It's a cool, little city
with a volatile past.

30:48.146 --> 30:49.948
Twice, they've had to rebuild

30:49.981 --> 30:52.417
after tsunamis
wiped out the downtown.

30:57.322 --> 31:00.291
[Music plays in distance]

31:00.325 --> 31:01.392
Hoelck: You hear that?

31:01.426 --> 31:03.228
What is that?

31:03.261 --> 31:05.063
[Music continues]

31:05.096 --> 31:07.098
Let's check this out.

31:07.131 --> 31:09.100
Hi.
<b></b>
Hello.

31:09.133 --> 31:10.635
Who's the puppy?
Hi, puppy.

31:10.668 --> 31:12.637
That's Sonny.
<b></b>
Hi, Sonny.

31:12.670 --> 31:22.647
♪♪

31:22.680 --> 31:31.356
♪♪

31:31.389 --> 31:33.591
How are you?
<b></b>
You're awesome.

31:33.625 --> 31:35.526
That was great.

31:35.560 --> 31:37.128
Is that like
an electric ukulele?

31:37.161 --> 31:39.864
Yeah.
<b></b>
What a cool shop.

31:39.898 --> 31:41.799
Believe it or not,
there was only three ukuleles

31:41.833 --> 31:43.501
from the start
of the shop.

31:43.534 --> 31:47.005
I soon realized this was
a serious instrument over here.

31:47.038 --> 31:48.473
So as you can see now,

31:48.506 --> 31:52.877
there's close
to 200 ukuleles here.

31:52.911 --> 31:54.545
Where --
where are you from?
<b></b>
Scotland.

31:54.579 --> 31:56.147
What are you doing out here?
<b></b>
[Strumming ukulele]

31:56.180 --> 31:57.782
Having fun.

31:57.815 --> 31:59.317
I looked up Hawaii on
the Internet

31:59.350 --> 32:01.619
and I came over here
and after an hour in Hilo,

32:01.653 --> 32:03.488
I said, "Okay, this is
where I want to live."

32:03.521 --> 32:05.023
Wow.
So what --

32:05.056 --> 32:07.892
what's your most prized
ukulele?

32:07.926 --> 32:10.228
Hoelck: Look at that one.
<b></b>
This is Hawaiian koa.

32:10.261 --> 32:13.131
Ah.
<b></b>
Which is now
protected by the state.

32:13.164 --> 32:14.732
And next to Brazilian
rosewood,

32:14.766 --> 32:16.401
it's the most expensive
wood in the world.

32:16.434 --> 32:17.735
Can't make it any --

32:17.769 --> 32:19.304
That's a $3,000 ukulele.
<b></b>
[Strums ukulele]

32:19.337 --> 32:21.472
Yeah, it is.
<b></b>
I only play the best.

32:21.506 --> 32:22.807
[Laughs]

32:22.840 --> 32:24.142
Well,
tell me about this area.

32:24.175 --> 32:25.910
This area seems --
seems super-cool.

32:25.944 --> 32:28.346
Well, if you look out there
where the soccer fields were,

32:28.379 --> 32:31.316
that actually used to be
the Downtown Hilo.

32:31.349 --> 32:34.686
And when the tsunami came,
it completely wiped it out.

32:34.719 --> 32:37.088
And rather than rebuild,

32:37.121 --> 32:39.023
they just put
soccer fields in there.

32:39.057 --> 32:41.826
My wife said that
she remembers as a child,

32:41.859 --> 32:44.062
her house being lifted up

32:44.095 --> 32:46.998
and moved
about 40 or 50 yards.

32:47.031 --> 32:49.567
That's crazy.
<b></b>
I've actually had to empty

32:49.600 --> 32:52.036
out the store
about seven times.

32:52.070 --> 32:53.404
You know, we get
the tsunami warnings,

32:53.438 --> 32:55.940
it's sirens go off
and it's pretty spooky.

32:55.974 --> 32:58.176
And then we get hurricanes
and --

32:58.209 --> 33:00.678
Active volcanoes.
<b></b>
Active volcanoes.

33:00.712 --> 33:04.215
I'm kind of scared
of Pele, to be honest.

33:04.248 --> 33:06.117
I feel like I would have
a crush on Pele

33:06.150 --> 33:08.252
and then she would turn me
into a tree like, right away.

33:08.286 --> 33:10.188
[Laughs]

33:11.656 --> 33:13.224
It's a pleasure to meet you.
Thank you so much.

33:13.257 --> 33:14.625
A pleasure to meet you, too.
Aloha.

33:14.659 --> 33:17.061
Aloha.

33:17.095 --> 33:20.131
♪ I know one thing
that's for sure ♪

33:20.164 --> 33:24.202
♪ Times running out,
can't wait no more ♪

33:24.235 --> 33:26.437
Patrick, where are you taking me
for breakfast?

33:26.471 --> 33:28.806
I kind of want
one of them coconuts.
<b></b>
Why not?

33:28.840 --> 33:30.408
Reedus:
Riding around this island,

33:30.441 --> 33:33.411
you meet a lot of people
like Ken, transplants,

33:33.444 --> 33:35.913
vagabonds,
those who packed up

33:35.947 --> 33:38.416
and came here
for their next chapter.

33:38.449 --> 33:41.119
That kind of life
is in my blood.

33:41.152 --> 33:44.889
Hey, is this where we went
with the Rock Island Riders?

33:44.922 --> 33:46.290
This is it, right?

33:46.324 --> 33:47.792
♪♪

33:47.825 --> 33:51.462
♪ I'm gonna take it
to the top now ♪

33:51.496 --> 33:54.599
♪ I feel alive
and I'm ready to go ♪

33:54.632 --> 33:56.934
We're on our way
to Mount Kilauea,

33:56.968 --> 33:59.604
because when you're on an island
with an active volcano,

33:59.637 --> 34:01.139
you head straight towards
the eruption...

34:01.172 --> 34:03.241
Here we go, here we go,
here we go.

34:03.274 --> 34:04.776
...unless you're hungry,
in which case,

34:04.809 --> 34:06.744
you look for some breakfast.

34:06.778 --> 34:09.447
Oh, here we go.
<b></b>
Uh-oh.

34:09.480 --> 34:11.149
[Grunts]

34:11.182 --> 34:13.184
Yeah,
this is going to be yummy.

34:13.217 --> 34:17.288
♪♪

34:17.321 --> 34:18.623
Aloha.
<b></b>
Hey, what's up, man?

34:18.656 --> 34:20.158
Hi. Norman.
<b></b>
Aloha.

34:20.191 --> 34:21.959
Nice to meet you.
<b></b>
How you guys doing today?

34:21.993 --> 34:23.528
Really good.

34:23.561 --> 34:25.797
We got all kind of good,
fresh fruit for you today.

34:25.830 --> 34:27.432
I'll have a coconut.

34:27.465 --> 34:29.267
♪♪

34:29.300 --> 34:31.169
Hoelck: You don't mess around
with that knife.

34:31.202 --> 34:32.637
You ever cut
yourself or never?

34:32.670 --> 34:34.038
Ah, yeah, yeah.
For sure.

34:34.072 --> 34:36.808
I just learned to
go easy with it.

34:36.841 --> 34:39.177
Where you from, dude?
<b></b>
Theo: I was born right here
in Hilo, man.

34:39.210 --> 34:41.546
Really?
<b></b>
Yeah, born and raised
right in Hilo.

34:41.579 --> 34:43.481
My brother right here.
<b></b>
What's up, man?

34:43.514 --> 34:45.450
Hi, how are you?
<b></b>
Thank you, sir.

34:45.483 --> 34:47.518
Did he show you
these ice cream beans?

34:47.552 --> 34:49.153
These ones came out
of the Amazon

34:49.187 --> 34:50.988
and they're kind
of new to Hawaii

34:51.022 --> 34:53.991
and it's been studied as a tree
to help heal the Amazon.

34:54.025 --> 34:55.493
They call it inga.

34:55.526 --> 34:57.128
I-N-G-A.
<b></b>
Mmm.

34:57.161 --> 34:58.996
Wow.
Those are great.
<b></b>
Yeah.

34:59.030 --> 35:02.166
They're like candy.
How'd you guys start doing this?

35:02.200 --> 35:05.169
We all started this
with my family in the year 2000.

35:05.203 --> 35:06.404
Wow.
<b></b>
Yeah.

35:06.437 --> 35:07.905
We started the homestead.

35:07.939 --> 35:10.141
The banana was one
of the first things we planted

35:10.174 --> 35:12.844
and then I have
my two daughters and my mom

35:12.877 --> 35:15.246
and other people
who help on the land and stuff.

35:15.279 --> 35:16.747
Hoelck: You guys got this
island figured out.

35:16.781 --> 35:20.184
Theo: Yeah. This one's called
the apple banana.

35:20.218 --> 35:22.186
And they're
all organic.
<b></b>
Mm.

35:22.220 --> 35:24.388
So much better than
your fancy grocery store.

35:24.422 --> 35:25.857
I know. It's like
a whole new experience.

35:25.890 --> 35:28.659
Simple.
So dense.

35:28.693 --> 35:30.194
You're going to do
it Hawaiian style.

35:30.228 --> 35:32.530
Coconut spoon
meat breakfast.

35:32.563 --> 35:34.098
And this is the stuff,
this is amazing.

35:34.132 --> 35:35.600
It's actually one of
the reasons why the Hawaiians

35:35.633 --> 35:37.435
used to have 10 kids
each right here.

35:37.468 --> 35:38.836
What do you mean?
<b></b>
[Laughs]

35:38.870 --> 35:41.038
Very fertile. [Laughs]
<b></b>
Lot of --

35:41.072 --> 35:42.507
Wow.
It's really good.

35:42.540 --> 35:44.075
Yeah,
it's good stuff.

35:44.108 --> 35:45.676
♪♪

35:45.710 --> 35:47.044
Hi!

35:47.078 --> 35:49.013
Hi, cutie.

35:49.046 --> 35:51.849
♪♪

35:51.883 --> 35:53.384
She feed
the peacocks coconut?

35:53.417 --> 35:54.852
Sanjaya: Yeah.
Our dogs eat coconut.

35:54.886 --> 35:56.888
Everything pretty much
eats the coconut.

35:56.921 --> 35:59.857
♪♪

35:59.891 --> 36:01.592
Are those the bananas
that we tried?

36:01.626 --> 36:03.895
Yep, you can see that --
that one rack right up there

36:03.928 --> 36:05.763
is pretty much
getting ripe.

36:05.796 --> 36:07.465
Once they start getting
full and round,

36:07.498 --> 36:09.367
you go and you follow
that trunk down

36:09.400 --> 36:11.469
and you cut down
that whole stock of the tree.

36:11.502 --> 36:12.870
♪♪

36:12.904 --> 36:14.138
Inga.

36:14.172 --> 36:15.740
♪♪

36:15.773 --> 36:19.110
Reedus: Get in there, Patrick!
Get in there!

36:19.143 --> 36:21.078
Come on, get in there.

36:21.112 --> 36:23.447
Do a big -- a big,
like a wedge, like --

36:23.481 --> 36:24.916
Yeah, yeah, yeah,
I got you.
<b></b>
You got it.

36:24.949 --> 36:27.285
Get me that banana, Patrick.
Come on.

36:27.318 --> 36:36.561
♪♪

36:36.594 --> 36:37.562
There we go.
<b></b>
Yeah.

36:37.595 --> 36:40.398
Timber! Watch out! Banana!

36:40.431 --> 36:42.833
There you go. Oh, yeah.

36:42.867 --> 36:44.101
Yeah!
<b></b>
You know
what I'm saying?

36:44.135 --> 36:47.238
His first rack of bananas!
<b></b>
Whoo!

36:47.271 --> 36:48.739
Thank you very much.
<b></b>
Thanks for this food.

36:48.773 --> 36:50.975
It's delicious.
<b></b>
Have a good trip, you guys.

36:51.008 --> 36:53.444
Reedus: Next stop, Kilauea,
and a potential date

36:53.477 --> 36:55.613
with a certain volcano goddess.

36:58.115 --> 37:00.818
Look at this, dude.
This doesn't even look real.

37:00.851 --> 37:03.020
This is a very,
very sacred area.
<b></b>
Yeah.

37:03.054 --> 37:05.489
You know how you just
get that shiver up your spine

37:05.523 --> 37:06.991
and it's like --?
<b></b>
I have it right now.

37:13.965 --> 37:17.735
ow, that's so pretty.your right.

37:17.768 --> 37:22.206
It looks so cool with all
this black sand down to it, too.

37:22.240 --> 37:24.408
Reedus: Leaving Hilo,
it's a 30-mile ride

37:24.442 --> 37:28.212
down Hawaii Belt Road
to Volcanoes National Park.

37:28.246 --> 37:30.381
Once there, a 20-mile,

37:30.414 --> 37:34.118
3,700-foot ascent up
Chain of Craters Road

37:34.151 --> 37:38.256
will give us the perfect
vantage point of Kilauea.

37:38.289 --> 37:41.092
Broadcaster:
Hawaii's famed volcanoes
are the most spectacular,

37:41.125 --> 37:44.395
yet the most readily
accessible in all the world.

37:44.428 --> 37:47.565
Reedus: Of the five volcanoes
that helped create this island,

37:47.598 --> 37:49.600
it's the only one still
currently erupting.

37:49.634 --> 37:53.070
♪ Say you'll meet me
in the hallway ♪
<b></b>
Wow.

37:53.104 --> 37:54.305
This is unreal.

37:54.338 --> 37:57.842
♪ And I will show you where ♪

37:57.875 --> 37:59.310
It's hard to imagine,

37:59.343 --> 38:01.012
but where these
lava rocks dominate

38:01.045 --> 38:03.180
the landscape,
there was once life.

38:03.214 --> 38:04.915
Smells like a forest fire.

38:04.949 --> 38:07.451
Trees, farms,
even villages.

38:07.485 --> 38:09.020
But as the lava spread,

38:09.053 --> 38:13.090
it engulfed everything
in its path.

38:13.124 --> 38:16.093
Over time, this area
will be completely reborn,

38:16.127 --> 38:18.763
but today, it's kind
of like riding on Mars.

38:18.796 --> 38:21.098
♪♪

38:21.132 --> 38:22.466
Look at that sunset,
man.

38:22.500 --> 38:27.772
Oh, my God.
Yeah, it's so beautiful.

38:27.805 --> 38:30.274
Whoa.

38:30.308 --> 38:32.543
That's a real gust.
<b></b>
Whoa.

38:32.576 --> 38:34.645
♪♪

38:34.679 --> 38:36.947
I feel like a sail
on a sailboat right now.

38:36.981 --> 38:39.450
Going to blow you
right off this cliff.

38:39.483 --> 38:42.353
Oh!
<b></b>
Oh!

38:42.386 --> 38:43.821
Stay low.

38:43.854 --> 38:46.524
I'm blowing over.

38:46.557 --> 38:49.660
Yo, I'm stopping.
It's crazy.

38:49.694 --> 38:51.495
50-mile-per-hour winds
and bikes

38:51.529 --> 38:54.632
don't really mix,
but we've made it.

38:54.665 --> 38:57.835
We're at Volcanoes
National Park.

38:57.868 --> 38:59.904
Honestly, I thought
I was going to flip over.

38:59.937 --> 39:02.373
It got real.
<b></b>
[Wind gusting]

39:02.406 --> 39:04.208
Just lay back.

39:07.011 --> 39:09.013
Whoo!

39:09.046 --> 39:11.482
We've done sand,
we've done ice.

39:11.515 --> 39:13.384
Fancy air.
Don't go far.

39:13.417 --> 39:16.887
And wind is my
least favorite.

39:16.921 --> 39:18.489
Look at this, dude.

39:18.522 --> 39:20.191
This doesn't
even look real.

39:23.561 --> 39:27.231
Wow,
this is really pretty.

39:27.264 --> 39:28.933
What's this called,
this little point?

39:28.966 --> 39:30.701
So this is the Holei Sea Arch.

39:30.735 --> 39:33.371
This arch is about
600 years old

39:33.404 --> 39:34.939
and you can see
how the erosions

39:34.972 --> 39:37.441
have been gradual over time

39:37.475 --> 39:39.710
and has a...
[Laughs]

39:39.744 --> 39:42.780
[Laughs]

39:42.813 --> 39:44.281
Is it always
this windy?

39:44.315 --> 39:45.950
No, we have really
high winds today.

39:45.983 --> 39:47.284
Oh. Look how --

39:47.318 --> 39:49.186
look how the waves
are like, wa-wah!

39:49.220 --> 39:50.721
Right?
<b></b>
Jessica: How was your ride
down the road?

39:50.755 --> 39:52.189
Hoelck: It was scary.

39:52.223 --> 39:53.691
Well, you guys came down
Chain of Craters Road,

39:53.724 --> 39:56.060
which is a notoriously
famous road.

39:56.093 --> 39:59.263
In 1969, Kilauea erupted
and covered it.

39:59.296 --> 40:01.298
And then the Park Service
built the road again.

40:01.332 --> 40:04.235
We'd rebuild it and Kilauea
would come and reclaim it again.

40:04.268 --> 40:05.770
How do you know it's not
going to erupt

40:05.803 --> 40:07.872
right now
and come down here?

40:07.905 --> 40:10.408
Actually, Kilauea is erupting
right now, from two spots.

40:10.441 --> 40:11.942
Let's get out of here.
<b></b>
[Laughs]

40:11.976 --> 40:13.711
Let's go.

40:13.744 --> 40:16.213
We have an eruption
from Kilauea,

40:16.247 --> 40:18.549
which is going into
the ocean just five miles

40:18.582 --> 40:20.050
from where we are.
<b></b>
Uh-huh.

40:20.084 --> 40:22.219
And we also have the one
back up at the summit.

40:22.253 --> 40:23.888
There's a giant lava lake.

40:23.921 --> 40:27.491
It's actually the legendary
home of Pele-honua-mea.

40:27.525 --> 40:29.326
She's our Hawaiian
volcano goddess.

40:29.360 --> 40:30.761
She's a bad ass.
<b></b>
Yes.

40:30.795 --> 40:32.897
Pele.
<b></b>
She has gotten jealous

40:32.930 --> 40:36.801
and changed a would-be suitor
into an ohia tree.

40:36.834 --> 40:40.905
She's struck some men dead
and there's many,

40:40.938 --> 40:44.175
many legends about this
very fiery volcano goddess.

40:44.208 --> 40:46.777
And her home is that
actual summit crater.

40:46.811 --> 40:48.746
You guys have to go up
and see the lava lake.

40:48.779 --> 40:50.781
Yeah, let's do it.

40:50.815 --> 40:52.016
[Wind gusting]

40:52.049 --> 40:53.517
[Laughs]

40:53.551 --> 40:58.189
♪♪

40:58.222 --> 40:59.757
Pele is real.

40:59.790 --> 41:01.959
In my eyes, she's real.

41:01.992 --> 41:03.794
Woman: We were taught when
we were growing up,

41:03.828 --> 41:08.265
it was basically
never disbelief.

41:08.299 --> 41:13.938
Respecting Pele and all
she stands for, it's...

41:13.971 --> 41:15.806
it's just what we do.

41:15.840 --> 41:18.943
Jessica: I'm taking you right
to the edge of Kilauea Volcano.

41:18.976 --> 41:22.780
Oh, wow.
<b></b>
Yeah, this is a very,
very sacred area.

41:22.813 --> 41:26.383
We're about a mile away
from that lava lake,

41:26.417 --> 41:28.219
which is about 800 feet across.

41:28.252 --> 41:32.223
The lava itself is about
75 feet below the surface.

41:32.256 --> 41:35.359
And it's 2,400° Fahrenheit.

41:35.392 --> 41:37.328
Whoa.
Wow.
<b></b>
Yeah.

41:37.361 --> 41:39.363
Does it ever like, puhk!,
in the air?

41:39.396 --> 41:40.965
We've actually
had the lava rise up

41:40.998 --> 41:42.466
and ooze
over that ledge,

41:42.500 --> 41:44.034
which was really
spectacular to see.

41:44.068 --> 41:45.669
Oh, wow.
<b></b>
But mostly,

41:45.703 --> 41:49.974
it's kind of this beautiful
type of effusive volcano.

41:50.007 --> 41:53.143
Pele is also all the steam
and the gasses rising from it,

41:53.177 --> 41:56.547
so a lot of times, these clouds
will take the shape of faces

41:56.580 --> 41:59.416
and a lot people feel like
they can really see Pele

41:59.450 --> 42:01.151
and connect
with the volcano goddess.

42:01.185 --> 42:02.520
Have you ever seen faces?

42:02.553 --> 42:04.922
All the time.
<b></b>
What happens
when you do?

42:04.955 --> 42:06.590
You know how you just
get that shiver

42:06.624 --> 42:08.259
up your spine
and it's like --?
<b></b>
I have it right now.

42:08.292 --> 42:10.694
Whoa.

42:10.728 --> 42:12.897
Reedus: Watching steam rise
from the glowing lava

42:12.930 --> 42:15.866
and you realize,
this place is alive.

42:15.900 --> 42:19.003
Volcanoes destroy,
but also create.

42:19.036 --> 42:20.571
And for the Hawaiian people,

42:20.604 --> 42:23.541
learning to coexist with
this ever-changing landscape

42:23.574 --> 42:26.377
has been paramount
to their survival,

42:26.410 --> 42:28.612
which is why their
reverence for Pele makes

42:28.646 --> 42:31.215
all the sense
in the world.

42:32.383 --> 42:36.554
I'm glad we finally got to do
this together.

42:36.587 --> 42:38.622
I know, it's amazing.

42:38.656 --> 42:39.924
I knew you would
hate this.

42:39.957 --> 42:42.259
[Laughs]

42:42.293 --> 42:43.694
Before coming to Hawaii,

42:43.727 --> 42:46.530
"aloha" was just a word,
a kitsch greeting

42:46.564 --> 42:48.933
to make tourist feel like
they're off the mainland,

42:48.966 --> 42:52.036
but being here,
I realize that aloha,

42:52.069 --> 42:55.439
the spirit of
the Hawaiian people, it's real.

42:55.472 --> 42:57.374
There's a hospitality
and inclusiveness

42:57.408 --> 42:59.276
on this island
that doesn't exist

42:59.310 --> 43:01.478
anywhere else in the world.

43:01.512 --> 43:03.614
All right.
This is amazing down here.

43:03.647 --> 43:05.416
Oh, yeah,
it's surreal.
